class="p">{</span><span class="x">Graph</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[\\x21-\\x7E]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Visible characters\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:lower:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">l</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="x">Lower</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[a-z]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Lowercase letters\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:print:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="x">Print</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[\\x20-\\x7E]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Visible characters and the space character\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:punct:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="x">Punct</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[][!&quot;#$%&amp;&#39;()*+,./:;&lt;=&gt;?@\\^_`{|}~-]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Punctuation characters\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:space:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">s</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">_s</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="x">Space</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code> or <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">s</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code>[ <a href="/wiki/%5Ct" class="mw-redirect" title="\\t">\\t</a><a href="/wiki/%5Cr" class="mw-redirect" title="\\r">\\r</a><a href="/wiki/%5Cn" class="mw-redirect" title="\\n">\\n</a><a href="/wiki/%5Cv" class="mw-redirect" title="\\v">\\v</a><a href="/wiki/%5Cf" class="mw-redirect" title="\\f">\\f</a>]</code>\n</td>\n<td><a href="/wiki/Whitespace_character" title="Whitespace character">Whitespace characters</a>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">S</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">S</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">S</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[^ \\t\\r\\n\\v\\f]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Non-whitespace characters\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:upper:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">u</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="x">Upper</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[A-Z]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Uppercase letters\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:xdigit:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">x</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">p</span><span class="p">{</span><span class="x">XDigit</span><span class="p">}</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td><code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[A-Fa-f0-9]</span><span class="w"></span></code>\n</td>\n<td>Hexadecimal digits\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>POSIX character classes can only be used within bracket expressions. For example, <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[[:upper:]</span><span class="nv">ab</span><span class="err">]</span><span class="w"></span></code> matches the uppercase letters and lowercase "a" and "b".\n</p><p>An additional non-POSIX class understood by some tools is <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:word:]</span><span class="w"></span></code>, which is usually defined as <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[:alnum:]</span><span class="w"></span></code> plus underscore. This reflects the fact that in many programming languages these are the characters that may be used in identifiers. The editor <a href="/wiki/Vim_(text_editor)" title="Vim (text editor)">Vim</a> further distinguishes <i>word</i> and <i>word-head</i> classes (using the notation <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">w</span><span class="w"></span></code> and <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">h</span><span class="w"></span></code>) since in many programming languages the characters that can begin an identifier are not the same as those that can occur in other positions: numbers are generally excluded, so an identifier would look like <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">h</span><span class="err">\\</span><span class="nv">w</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="w"></span></code> or <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel" dir="ltr"><span class="s">[[:alpha:]</span><span class="nv">_</span><span class="err">]</span><span class="s">[[:alnum:]</span><span class="nv">_</span><span class="err">]</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="w"></span></code> in POSIX notation.\n</p><p>Note that what the POSIX regex standards call <i>character classes</i> are commonly referred to as <i>POSIX character classes</i> in other regex flavors which support them. With most other regex flavors, the term <i>character class</i> is used to describe what POSIX calls <i>bracket expressions</i>.\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Perl_and_PCRE">Perl and PCRE</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Perl and PCRE">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Perl_Compatible_Regular_Expressions" title="Perl Compatible Regular Expressions">Perl Compatible Regular Expressions</a></div>\n<p>Because of its expressive power and (relative) ease of reading, many other utilities and programming languages have adopted syntax similar to <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">Perl</a>\'s \xe2\x80\x94 for example, <a href="/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)">Java</a>, <a href="/wiki/JavaScript" title="JavaScript">JavaScript</a>, <a href="/wiki/Julia_(programming_language)" title="Julia (programming language)">Julia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title="Python (programming language)">Python</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ruby_(programming_language)" title="Ruby (programming language)">Ruby</a>, <a href="/wiki/Qt_(software)" title="Qt (software)">Qt</a>, Microsoft\'s <a href="/wiki/.NET_Framework" title=".NET Framework">.NET Framework</a>, and <a href="/wiki/XML_Schema_(W3C)" title="XML Schema (W3C)">XML Schema</a>. Some languages and tools such as <a href="/wiki/Boost_C%2B%2B_Libraries" class="mw-redirect" title="Boost C++ Libraries">Boost</a> and <a href="/wiki/PHP" title="PHP">PHP</a> support multiple regex flavors. Perl-derivative regex implementations are not identical and usually implement a subset of features found in Perl 5.0, released in 1994. Perl sometimes does incorporate features initially found in other languages. For example, Perl 5.10 implements syntactic extensions originally developed in PCRE and Python.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Lazy_matching">Lazy matching</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Lazy matching">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In Python and some other implementations (e.g. Java), the three common quantifiers (<code>*</code>, <code>+</code> and <code>?</code>) are <a href="/wiki/Greedy_algorithm" title="Greedy algorithm">greedy</a> by default because they match as many characters as possible.<sup id="cite_ref-py-re_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-py-re-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> The regex <code>".+"</code> (including the double-quotes) applied to the string\n</p>\n<pre>"Ganymede," he continued, "is the largest moon in the Solar System."\n</pre>\n<p>matches the entire line (because the entire line begins and ends with a double-quote) instead of matching only the first part, <code>"Ganymede,"</code>. The aforementioned quantifiers may, however, be made <i>lazy</i> or <i>minimal</i> or <i>reluctant</i>, matching as few characters as possible, by appending a question mark: <code>".+?"</code> matches only <code>"Ganymede,"</code>.<sup id="cite_ref-py-re_32-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-py-re-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>However, the whole sentence can still be matched in some circumstances. The question-mark operator does not change the meaning of the dot operator, so this still can match the double-quotes in the input. A pattern like <code>".*?" EOF</code> will still match the whole input if this is the string:\n</p>\n<pre>"Ganymede," he continued, "is the largest moon in the Solar System." EOF\n</pre>\n<p>To ensure that the double-quotes cannot be part of the match, the dot has to be replaced (e.g. <code>"[^"]*"</code>). This will match a quoted text part without additional double-quotes in it. (By removing possibilities for a fixed suffix to be matched, one also transforms the lazy-match to a greedy-match.)<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Possessive_matching">Possessive matching</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Possessive matching">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In Java, quantifiers may be made <i>possessive</i> by appending a plus sign, which disables backing off (in a backtracking engine), even if doing so would allow the overall match to succeed:<sup id="cite_ref-es-re_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-es-re-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> While the regex <code>".*"</code> applied to the string\n</p>\n<pre>"Ganymede," he continued, "is the largest moon in the Solar System."\n</pre>\n<p>matches the entire line, the regex <code>".*+"</code> does <em>not match at all</em>, because <code>.*+</code> consumes the entire input, including the final <code>"</code>. Thus, possessive quantifiers are most useful with negated character classes, e.g. <code>"[^"]*+"</code>, which matches <code>"Ganymede,"</code> when applied to the same string.\n</p><p>Another common extension serving the same function is atomic grouping, which disables backtracking for a parenthesized group. The typical syntax is <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r886049734">.mw-parser-output .monospaced{font-family:monospace,monospace}</style><span class="monospaced">(?&gt;group)</span>. For example, while <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">^(wi|w)i$</span> matches both <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">wi</span> and <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">wii</span>, <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">^(?&gt;wi|w)i$</span> only matches <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">wii</span> because the engine is forbidden from backtracking and try with setting the group as "w".<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Possessive quantifiers are easier to implement than greedy and lazy quantifiers, and are typically more efficient at runtime.<sup id="cite_ref-es-re_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-es-re-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Patterns_for_non-regular_languages">Patterns for non-regular languages</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Patterns for non-regular languages">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Many features found in virtually all modern regular expression libraries provide an expressive power that exceeds the <a href="/wiki/Regular_language" title="Regular language">regular languages</a>. For example, many implementations allow grouping subexpressions with parentheses and recalling the value they match in the same expression (<i><span id="backreferences">backreferences</span></i>). This means that, among other things, a pattern can match strings of repeated words like "papa" or "WikiWiki", called <i>squares</i> in formal language theory. The pattern for these strings is <code>(.+)\\1</code>.\n</p><p>The language of squares is not regular, nor is it <a href="/wiki/Context-free_language" title="Context-free language">context-free</a>, due to the <a href="/wiki/Pumping_lemma_for_context-free_languages" title="Pumping lemma for context-free languages">pumping lemma</a>. However, <a href="/wiki/Pattern_matching" title="Pattern matching">pattern matching</a> with an unbounded number of backreferences, as supported by numerous modern tools, is still <a href="/wiki/Context-sensitive_language" title="Context-sensitive language">context sensitive</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> The general problem of matching any number of backreferences is <a href="/wiki/NP-complete" class="mw-redirect" title="NP-complete">NP-complete</a>, growing exponentially by the number of backref groups used.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>However, many tools, libraries, and engines that provide such constructions still use the term <i>regular expression</i> for their patterns. This has led to a nomenclature where the term regular expression has different meanings in <a href="/wiki/Formal_language" title="Formal language">formal language theory</a> and pattern matching. For this reason, some people have taken to using the term <i>regex</i>, <i>regexp</i>, or simply <i>pattern</i> to describe the latter. <a href="/wiki/Larry_Wall" title="Larry Wall">Larry Wall</a>, author of the Perl programming language, writes in an essay about the design of Raku:\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r960796168">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class="templatequote"><p>"Regular expressions" [\xe2\x80\xa6] are only marginally related to real regular expressions. Nevertheless, the term has grown with the capabilities of our pattern matching engines, so I\'m not going to try to fight linguistic necessity here. I will, however, generally call them "regexes" (or "regexen", when I\'m in an Anglo-Saxon mood).<sup id="cite_ref-Apocalypse5_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Apocalypse5-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>\n<table id="lookbehind" class="infobox wikitable">\n<tbody><tr>\n<th>Assertion</th>\n<th>Lookbehind</th>\n<th>Lookahead\n</th></tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Positive\n</th>\n<td style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;">(?<b>&lt;=</b><span style="background:black;color:white;font-size:80%;padding:0 0.5ex;border-radius:2ex;">pattern</span>)\n</td>\n<td style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;">(?<b>=</b><span style="background:black;color:white;font-size:80%;padding:0 0.5ex;border-radius:2ex;">pattern</span>)\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Negative\n</th>\n<td style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;">(?<b>&lt;!</b><span style="background:black;color:white;font-size:80%;padding:0 0.5ex;border-radius:2ex;">pattern</span>)\n</td>\n<td style="text-align:center;font-size:125%;">(?<span style="padding:1px;"><b>!</b></span><span style="background:black;color:white;font-size:80%;padding:0 0.5ex;border-radius:2ex;">pattern</span>)\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan="3">Look-behind and look-ahead assertions<br />in <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">Perl</a> regular expressions\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>Other features not found in describing regular languages include assertions. These include the ubiquitous <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">^</span> and <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r886049734"/><span class="monospaced">$</span>, as well as some more sophisticated extensions like lookaround. They define the surrounding of a match and don\'t spill into the match itself, a feature only relevant for the use case of string searching. Some of them can be simulated in a regular language by treating the surroundings as a part of the language as well.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Implementations_and_running_times"><span class="anchor" id="Implementations"></span>Implementations and running times</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Implementations and running times">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>There are at least three different <a href="/wiki/Algorithm" title="Algorithm">algorithms</a> that decide whether and how a given regex matches a string.\n</p><p>The oldest and fastest relies on a result in formal language theory that allows every <a href="/wiki/Nondeterministic_finite_automaton" title="Nondeterministic finite automaton">nondeterministic finite automaton</a> (NFA) to be transformed into a <a href="/wiki/Deterministic_finite_automaton" title="Deterministic finite automaton">deterministic finite automaton</a> (DFA). The DFA can be constructed explicitly and then run on the resulting input string one symbol at a time. Constructing the DFA for a regular expression of size <i>m</i> has the time and memory cost of <a href="/wiki/Big_O_notation" title="Big O notation"><i>O</i></a>(2<sup><i>m</i></sup>), but it can be run on a string of size <i>n</i> in time <i>O</i>(<i>n</i>).  Note that the size of the expression is the size after abbreviations, such as numeric quantifiers, have been expanded.\n</p><p>An alternative approach is to simulate the NFA directly, essentially building each DFA state on demand and then discarding it at the next step. This keeps the DFA implicit and avoids the exponential construction cost, but running cost rises to <i>O</i>(<i>mn</i>). The explicit approach is called the DFA algorithm and the implicit approach the NFA algorithm. Adding caching to the NFA algorithm is often called the "lazy DFA" algorithm, or just the DFA algorithm without making a distinction. These algorithms are fast, but using them for recalling grouped subexpressions, lazy quantification, and similar features is tricky.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> Modern implementations include the re1-re2-sregex family based on Cox\'s code.\n</p><p>The third algorithm is to match the pattern against the input string by <a href="/wiki/Backtracking" title="Backtracking">backtracking</a>. This algorithm is commonly called NFA, but this terminology can be confusing. Its running time can be exponential, which simple implementations exhibit when matching against expressions like <code class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl" id="" style="" dir="ltr"><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">a</span><span class="o">|</span><span class="n">aa</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">b</span></code> that contain both alternation and unbounded quantification and force the algorithm to consider an exponentially increasing number of sub-cases. This behavior can cause a security problem called <a href="/wiki/Regular_expression_Denial_of_Service" class="mw-redirect" title="Regular expression Denial of Service">Regular expression Denial of Service</a> (ReDoS).\n</p><p>Although backtracking implementations only give an exponential guarantee in the worst case, they provide much greater flexibility and expressive power. For example, any implementation which allows the use of backreferences, or implements the various extensions introduced by Perl, must include some kind of backtracking. Some implementations try to provide the best of both algorithms by first running a fast DFA algorithm, and revert to a potentially slower backtracking algorithm only when a backreference is encountered during the match. GNU grep (and the underlying gnulib DFA) uses such a strategy.<sup id="cite_ref-40" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Sublinear runtime algorithms have been achieved using <a href="/wiki/Boyer%E2%80%93Moore_string-search_algorithm" title="Boyer\xe2\x80\x93Moore string-search algorithm">Boyer-Moore (BM) based algorithms</a> and related DFA optimization techniques such as the reverse scan.<sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> GNU grep, which supports a wide variety of POSIX syntaxes and extensions, uses BM for a first-pass prefiltering, and then uses an implicit DFA. Wu <a href="/wiki/Agrep" title="Agrep">agrep</a>, which implements approximate matching, combines the prefiltering into the DFA in BDM (backward DAWG matching). NR-grep\'s BNDM extends the BDM technique with Shift-Or bit-level parallelism.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A few theoretical alternatives to backtracking for backreferences exist, and their "exponents" are tamer in that they are only related to the number of backreferences, a fixed property of some regexp languages such as POSIX. One naive method that duplicates a non-backtracking NFA for each backreference note has a complexity of <span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\\displaystyle {\\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})}">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n            <mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>n</mi>\n          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n            <mn>2</mn>\n            <mi>k</mi>\n            <mo>+</mo>\n            <mn>2</mn>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle {\\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/361c3d5a02535be4d1eadd7ff71c859ce4aab804" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:9.023ex; height:3.176ex;" alt="{\\displaystyle {\\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+2})}"/></span> time and <span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\\displaystyle {\\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})}">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">\n        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n            <mi mathvariant="normal">O</mi>\n          </mrow>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>n</mi>\n          <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">\n            <mn>2</mn>\n            <mi>k</mi>\n            <mo>+</mo>\n            <mn>1</mn>\n          </mrow>\n        </msup>\n        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\\displaystyle {\\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/422ccb4d3778a47ae05dff4c03e335ba8c12fe8b" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:9.023ex; height:3.176ex;" alt="{\\displaystyle {\\mathrm {O} }(n^{2k+1})}"/></span> space for a haystack of length n and k backreferences in the RegExp.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> A very recent theoretical work based on memory automata gives a tighter bound based on "active" variable nodes used, and a polynomial possibility for some backreferenced regexps.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Unicode">Unicode</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Unicode">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In theoretical terms, any token set can be matched by regular expressions as long as it is pre-defined. In terms of historical implementations, regexes were originally written to use <a href="/wiki/American_Standard_Code_for_Information_Interchange" class="mw-redirect" title="American Standard Code for Information Interchange">ASCII</a> characters as their token set though regex libraries have supported numerous other <a href="/wiki/Character_set" class="mw-redirect" title="Character set">character sets</a>. Many modern regex engines offer at least some support for <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a>. In most respects it makes no difference what the character set is, but some issues do arise when extending regexes to support Unicode.\n</p>\n<ul><li><b>Supported encoding</b>. Some regex libraries expect to work on some particular encoding instead of on abstract Unicode characters. Many of these require the <a href="/wiki/UTF-8" title="UTF-8">UTF-8</a> encoding, while others might expect <a href="/wiki/UTF-16" title="UTF-16">UTF-16</a>, or <a href="/wiki/UTF-32" title="UTF-32">UTF-32</a>. In contrast, Perl and Java are agnostic on encodings, instead operating on decoded characters internally.</li>\n<li><b>Supported Unicode range</b>. Many regex engines support only the <a href="/wiki/Basic_Multilingual_Plane" class="mw-redirect" title="Basic Multilingual Plane">Basic Multilingual Plane</a>, that is, the characters which can be encoded with only 16 bits. Currently (as of 2016) only a few regex engines (e.g., Perl\'s and Java\'s) can handle the full 21-bit Unicode range.</li>\n<li><b>Extending ASCII-oriented constructs to Unicode</b>. For example, in ASCII-based implementations, character ranges of the form <code>[x-y]</code> are valid wherever <i>x</i> and <i>y</i> have <a href="/wiki/Code_point" title="Code point">code points</a> in the range [0x00,0x7F] and codepoint(<i>x</i>) \xe2\x89\xa4 codepoint(<i>y</i>). The natural extension of such character ranges to Unicode would simply change the requirement that the endpoints lie in [0x00,0x7F] to the requirement that they lie in [0x0000,0x10FFFF]. However, in practice this is often not the case. Some implementations, such as that of <a href="/wiki/Gawk_(GNU_package)" class="mw-redirect" title="Gawk (GNU package)">gawk</a>, do not allow character ranges to cross Unicode blocks. A range like [0x61,0x7F] is valid since both endpoints fall within the Basic Latin block, as is [0x0530,0x0560] since both endpoints fall within the Armenian block, but a range like [0x0061,0x0532] is invalid since it includes multiple Unicode blocks. Other engines, such as that of the <a href="/wiki/Vim_(text_editor)" title="Vim (text editor)">Vim</a> editor, allow block-crossing but the character values must not be more than 256 apart.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><b>Case insensitivity</b>. Some case-insensitivity flags affect only the ASCII characters. Other flags affect all characters. Some engines have two different flags, one for ASCII, the other for Unicode. Exactly which characters belong to the POSIX classes also varies.</li>\n<li><b>Cousins of case insensitivity</b>. As ASCII has case distinction, case insensitivity became a logical feature in text searching. Unicode introduced alphabetic scripts without case like <a href="/wiki/Devan%C4%81gar%C4%AB" class="mw-redirect" title="Devan\xc4\x81gar\xc4\xab">Devanagari</a>. For these, <a href="/wiki/Case_sensitivity" title="Case sensitivity">case sensitivity</a> is not applicable. For scripts like Chinese, another distinction seems logical: between traditional and simplified. In Arabic scripts, insensitivity to <a href="/wiki/IMFI" title="IMFI">initial, medial, final, and isolated position</a> may be desired. In Japanese, insensitivity between <a href="/wiki/Hiragana" title="Hiragana">hiragana</a> and <a href="/wiki/Katakana" title="Katakana">katakana</a> is sometimes useful.</li>\n<li><b>Normalization</b>. Unicode has <a href="/wiki/Unicode#Combining_characters" title="Unicode">combining characters</a>. Like old typewriters, plain letters can be followed by one or more non-spacing symbols (usually diacritics like accent marks) to form a single printing character, but also provides precomposed characters, i.e. characters that already include one or more combining characters. A sequence of a character + combining character should be matched with the identical single precomposed character. The process of standardizing sequences of characters + combining characters is called normalization.</li>\n<li><b>New control codes</b>. Unicode introduced amongst others, <a href="/wiki/Byte_order_mark" title="Byte order mark">byte order marks</a> and text direction markers. These codes might have to be dealt with in a special way.</li>\n<li><b>Introduction of character classes for Unicode blocks, scripts, and numerous other character properties</b>. Block properties are much less useful than script properties, because a block can have code points from several different scripts, and a script can have code points from several different blocks.<sup id="cite_ref-unicode_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-unicode-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">Perl</a> and the <code><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/util/regex/package-summary.html">java.util.regex</a></code> library, properties of the form <code>\\p{InX}</code> or <code>\\p{Block=X}</code> match characters in block <i>X</i> and <code>\\P{InX}</code> or <code>\\P{Block=X}</code> matches code points not in that block. Similarly, <code>\\p{Armenian}</code>, <code>\\p{IsArmenian}</code>, or <code>\\p{Script=Armenian}</code> matches any character in the Armenian script. In general, <code>\\p{X}</code> matches any character with either the binary property <i>X</i> or the general category <i>X</i>. For example, <code>\\p{Lu}</code>, <code>\\p{Uppercase_Letter}</code>, or <code>\\p{GC=Lu}</code> matches any uppercase letter. Binary properties that are <i>not</i> general categories include <code>\\p{White_Space}</code>, <code>\\p{Alphabetic}</code>, <code>\\p{Math}</code>, and <code>\\p{Dash}</code>. Examples of non-binary properties are <code>\\p{Bidi_Class=Right_to_Left}</code>, <code>\\p{Word_Break=A_Letter}</code>, and <code>\\p{Numeric_Value=10}</code>.</li></ul>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Uses">Uses</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Uses">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Regexes are useful in a wide variety of text processing tasks, and more generally <a href="/wiki/String_processing" class="mw-redirect" title="String processing">string processing</a>, where the data need not be textual. Common applications include <a href="/wiki/Data_validation" title="Data validation">data validation</a>, <a href="/wiki/Data_scraping" title="Data scraping">data scraping</a> (especially <a href="/wiki/Web_scraping" title="Web scraping">web scraping</a>), <a href="/wiki/Data_wrangling" title="Data wrangling">data wrangling</a>, simple <a href="/wiki/Parsing" title="Parsing">parsing</a>, the production of <a href="/wiki/Syntax_highlighting" title="Syntax highlighting">syntax highlighting</a> systems, and many other tasks.\n</p><p>While regexes would be useful on Internet <a href="/wiki/Search_engine_(computing)" title="Search engine (computing)">search engines</a>, processing them across the entire database could consume excessive computer resources depending on the complexity and design of the regex. Although in many cases system administrators can run regex-based queries internally, most search engines do not offer regex support to the public. Notable exceptions include <a href="/wiki/Google_Code_Search" title="Google Code Search">Google Code Search</a> and <a href="/wiki/Exalead" title="Exalead">Exalead</a>. However, Google Code Search was shut down in January 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Examples">Examples</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Examples">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The specific syntax rules vary depending on the specific implementation, <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming language</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Library_(computing)" title="Library (computing)">library</a> in use. Additionally, the functionality of regex implementations can vary between <a href="/wiki/Software_versioning" title="Software versioning">versions</a>.\n</p><p>Because regexes can be difficult to both explain and understand without examples, interactive websites for testing regexes are a useful resource for learning regexes by experimentation.\nThis section provides a basic description of some of the properties of regexes by way of illustration.\n</p><p>The following conventions are used in the examples.<sup id="cite_ref-clarify000_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-clarify000-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<pre>metacharacter(s)&#160;;; the metacharacters column specifies the regex syntax being demonstrated\n=~ m//           ;; indicates a regex <i>match</i> operation in Perl\n=~ s///          ;; indicates a regex <i>substitution</i> operation in Perl\n</pre>\n<p>Also worth noting is that these regexes are all Perl-like syntax. Standard <a href="#POSIX_Basic_Regular_Expressions">POSIX</a> regular expressions are different.\n</p><p>Unless otherwise indicated, the following examples conform to the <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">Perl</a> programming language, release 5.8.8, January 31, 2006. This means that other implementations may lack support for some parts of the syntax shown here (e.g. basic vs. extended regex, <code>\\( \\)</code> vs. <code>()</code>, or lack of <code>\\d</code> instead of <a href="/wiki/POSIX" title="POSIX">POSIX</a> <code>[:digit:]</code>).\n</p><p>The syntax and conventions used in these examples coincide with that of other programming environments as well.<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<table class="wikitable">\n<tbody><tr>\n<th>Meta&#173;character(s)\n</th>\n<th>Description\n</th>\n<th>Example<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>\n</th></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>.</code>\n</th>\n<td>Normally matches any character except a newline. <br />Within square brackets the dot is literal.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/...../</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 has length &gt;= 5.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello World\n has length &gt;= 5.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>( )</code>\n</th>\n<td>Groups a series of pattern elements to a single element. <br />When you match a pattern within parentheses, you can use any of <code>$1</code>, <code>$2</code>, ... later to refer to the previously matched pattern.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/(H..).(o..)/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;We matched &#39;$1&#39; and &#39;$2&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>We matched &#39;Hel&#39; and &#39;o W&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>+</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the preceding pattern element one or more times.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/l+/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There are one or more consecutive letter \\&quot;l\\&quot;&#39;s in $string1.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There are one or more consecutive letter &quot;l&quot;&#39;s in Hello World.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>?</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the preceding pattern element zero or one time.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/H.?e/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There is an &#39;H&#39; and a &#39;e&#39; separated by &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;0-1 characters (e.g., He Hue Hee).\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There is an &#39;H&#39; and a &#39;e&#39; separated by 0-1 characters (e.g., He Hue Hee).\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>?</code>\n</th>\n<td>Modifies the <code>*</code>, <code>+</code>, <code>?</code> or <code>{M,N}</code>\'d regex that comes before to match as few times as possible.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/(l.+?o)/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;The non-greedy match with &#39;l&#39; followed by one or &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;more characters is &#39;llo&#39; rather than &#39;llo Wo&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>The non-greedy match with &#39;l&#39; followed by one or more characters is &#39;llo&#39; rather than &#39;llo Wo&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>*</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the preceding pattern element zero or more times.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/el*o/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There is an &#39;e&#39; followed by zero to many &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;&#39;l&#39; followed by &#39;o&#39; (e.g., eo, elo, ello, elllo).\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There is an &#39;e&#39; followed by zero to many &#39;l&#39; followed by &#39;o&#39; (e.g., eo, elo, ello, elllo).\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>{M,N}</code>\n</th>\n<td>Denotes the minimum M and the maximum N match count.<br />N can be omitted and M can be 0: <code>{M}</code> matches "exactly" M times; <code>{M,}</code> matches "at least" M times; <code>{0,N}</code> matches "at most" N times.<br /><code>x* y+ z?</code> is thus equivalent to <code>x{0,} y{1,} z{0,1}</code>.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/l{1,2}/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There exists a substring with at least 1 &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;and at most 2 l&#39;s in $string1\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There exists a substring with at least 1 and at most 2 l&#39;s in Hello World\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>[\xe2\x80\xa6]</code>\n</th>\n<td>Denotes a set of possible character matches.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/[aeiou]+/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 contains one or more vowels.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello World\n contains one or more vowels.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>|</code>\n</th>\n<td>Separates alternate possibilities.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/(Hello|Hi|Pogo)/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 contains at least one of Hello, Hi, or Pogo.&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello World\n contains at least one of Hello, Hi, or Pogo.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\b</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches a zero-width boundary between a word-class character (see next) and either a non-word class character or an edge; same as\n<p><code>(^\\w|\\w$|\\W\\w|\\w\\W)</code>.\n</p>\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/llo\\b/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There is a word that ends with &#39;llo&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There is a word that ends with &#39;llo&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\w</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches an alphanumeric character, including "_"; <br />same as <code>[A-Za-z0-9_]</code> in ASCII, and\n<dl><dd><code>[\\p{Alphabetic}<wbr />\\p{GC=Mark}<wbr />\\p{GC=Decimal_Number}<wbr />\\p{GC=Connector_Punctuation}]</code></dd></dl>\n<p>in Unicode,<sup id="cite_ref-unicode_46-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-unicode-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> where the <code>Alphabetic</code> property contains more than Latin letters, and the <code>Decimal_Number</code> property contains more than Arab digits.\n</p>\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/\\w/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There is at least one alphanumeric &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;character in $string1 (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, _).\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There is at least one alphanumeric character in Hello World\n (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, _).\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\W</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches a <i>non</i>-alphanumeric character, excluding "_"; <br />same as <code>[^A-Za-z0-9_]</code> in ASCII, and\n<dl><dd><code>[^\\p{Alphabetic}<wbr />\\p{GC=Mark}<wbr />\\p{GC=Decimal_Number}<wbr />\\p{GC=Connector_Punctuation}]</code></dd></dl>\n<p>in Unicode.\n</p>\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/\\W/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;The space between Hello and &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;World is not alphanumeric.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>The space between Hello and World is not alphanumeric.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\s</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches a whitespace character, <br />which in ASCII are tab, line feed, form feed, carriage return, and space; <br />in Unicode, also matches no-<wbr />break spaces, next line, and the variable-<wbr />width spaces (amongst others).\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/\\s.*\\s/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;In $string1 there are TWO whitespace characters, which may&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot; be separated by other characters.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>In Hello World\n there are TWO whitespace characters, which may be separated by other characters.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\S</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches anything <i>but</i> a whitespace.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/\\S.*\\S/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;In $string1 there are TWO non-whitespace characters, which&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot; may be separated by other characters.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>In Hello World\n there are TWO non-whitespace characters, which may be separated by other characters.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\d</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches a digit; <br />same as <code>[0-9]</code> in ASCII; <br />in Unicode, same as the <code>\\p{Digit}</code> or <code>\\p{GC=Decimal_Number}</code> property, which itself the same as the <code>\\p{Numeric_Type=Decimal}</code> property.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;99 bottles of beer on the wall.&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/(\\d+)/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$1 is the first number in &#39;$string1&#39;\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>99 is the first number in &#39;99 bottles of beer on the wall.&#39;\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\D</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches a non-digit; <br />same as <code>[^0-9]</code> in ASCII or <code>\\P{Digit}</code> in Unicode.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/\\D/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;There is at least one character in $string1&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot; that is not a digit.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>There is at least one character in Hello World\n that is not a digit.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>^</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the beginning of a line or string.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/^He/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 starts with the characters &#39;He&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello World\n starts with the characters &#39;He&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>$</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the end of a line or string.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/rld$/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 is a line or string &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;that ends with &#39;rld&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello World\n is a line or string that ends with &#39;rld&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\A</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the beginning of a string (but not an internal line).\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello\\nWorld\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/\\AH/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 is a string &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;that starts with &#39;H&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello\nWorld\n is a string that starts with &#39;H&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>\\z</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches the end of a string (but not an internal line).<sup id="cite_ref-Perl_Best_Practices_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Perl_Best_Practices-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup>\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello\\nWorld\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/d\\n\\z/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 is a string &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n  <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;that ends with &#39;d\\\\n&#39;.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello\nWorld\n is a string that ends with &#39;d\\n&#39;.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr>\n<tr>\n<th><code>[^\xe2\x80\xa6]</code>\n</th>\n<td>Matches every character except the ones inside brackets.\n</td>\n<td><div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-perl mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s">&quot;Hello World\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="k">if</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">$string1</span> <span class="o">=~</span> <span class="sr">m/[^abc]/</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">{</span>\n <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;$string1 contains a character other than &quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n <span class="k">print</span> <span class="s">&quot;a, b, and c.\\n&quot;</span><span class="p">;</span>\n<span class="p">}</span>\n</pre></div>\n<p><b>Output:</b>\n</p>\n<div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr"><pre><span></span>Hello World\n contains a character other than a, b, and c.\n</pre></div>\n</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Induction">Induction</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Induction">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Induction_of_regular_languages" title="Induction of regular languages">Induction of regular languages</a></div>\n<p>Regular expressions can often be created ("induced" or "learned") based on a set of example strings. This is known as the <a href="/wiki/Induction_of_regular_languages" title="Induction of regular languages">induction of regular languages</a>, and is part of the general problem of <a href="/wiki/Grammar_induction" title="Grammar induction">grammar induction</a> in <a href="/wiki/Computational_learning_theory" title="Computational learning theory">computational learning theory</a>. Formally, given examples of strings in a regular language, and perhaps also given examples of strings <i>not</i> in that regular language, it is possible to induce a grammar for the language, i.e., a regular expression that generates that language. Not all regular languages can be induced in this way (see <a href="/wiki/Language_identification_in_the_limit" title="Language identification in the limit">language identification in the limit</a>), but many can. For example, the set of examples {1, 10, 100}, and negative set (of counterexamples) {11, 1001, 101, 0} can be used to induce the regular expression 1\xe2\x8b\x850* (1 followed by zero or more 0s).\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Comparison_of_regular-expression_engines" title="Comparison of regular-expression engines">Comparison of regular-expression engines</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Extended_Backus%E2%80%93Naur_form" title="Extended Backus\xe2\x80\x93Naur form">Extended Backus\xe2\x80\x93Naur form</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Matching_wildcards" title="Matching wildcards">Matching wildcards</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Regular_tree_grammar" title="Regular tree grammar">Regular tree grammar</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Thompson%27s_construction" title="Thompson&#39;s construction">Thompson\'s construction</a> \xe2\x80\x93 converts a regular expression into an equivalent <a href="/wiki/Nondeterministic_finite_automaton" title="Nondeterministic finite automaton">nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA)</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Regular_expression&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span Retrieved <span class="nowrap">4 May</span> 2019</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Google+Blog&amp;rft.atitle=A+fall+sweep&amp;rft.date=2011-10-24&amp;rft.aulast=Horowitz&amp;rft.aufirst=Bradley&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fgoogleblog.blogspot.com%2F2011%2F10%2Ffall-sweep.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARegular+expression" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r982806391"/></span>\n</li>\n<li id="cite_note-clarify000-48"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-clarify000_48-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The character \'m\' is not always required to specify a <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">Perl</a> match operation. For example, <code>m/[^abc]/</code> could also be rendered as <code>/[^abc]/</code>. The \'m\' is only necessary if the user wishes to specify a match operation without using a forward-slash as the regex <a href="/wiki/Delimiter" title="Delimiter">delimiter</a>. Sometimes it is useful to specify an alternate regex delimiter in order to avoid "<a href="/wiki/Delimiter_collision" class="mw-redirect" title="Delimiter collision">delimiter collision</a>". See \'<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://perldoc.perl.org/perlre.html">perldoc perlre</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20091231010052/http://perldoc.perl.org/perlre.html">Archived</a> 2009-12-31 at the <a href="/wiki/Wayback_Machine" title="Wayback Machine">Wayback Machine</a>\' for more details.</span>\n</li>\n<li id="cite_note-49"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-49">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">E.g., see <i><a href="/wiki/Java_(programming_language)" title="Java (programming language)">Java</a> <a href="/wiki/O%27Reilly_Media#In_a_Nutshell" title="O&#39;Reilly Media">in a Nutshell</a></i>, p. 213; <i><a href="/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title="Python (programming language)">Python</a> Scripting for Computational Science</i>, p. 320; Programming <a href="/wiki/PHP" title="PHP">PHP</a>, p. 106.</span>\n</li>\n<li id="cite_note-50"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Note that all the if statements return a TRUE value</span>\n</li>\n<li id="cite_note-Perl_Best_Practices-51"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Perl_Best_Practices_51-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFConway2005" class="citation book cs1"><a href="/wiki/Damian_Conway" title="Damian Conway">Conway, Damian</a> (2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.scribd.com/doc/15491004/Perl-Best-Practices">"Regular Expressions, End of String"</a>. <i>Perl Best Practices</i>. <a href="/wiki/O%27Reilly_Media" title="O&#39;Reilly Media">O\'Reilly</a>. p.&#160;240. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-596-00173-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-596-00173-5"><bdi>978-0-596-00173-5</bdi></a>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20201007183212/https://www.scribd.com/book/15491004/Perl-Best-Practices-Standards-and-Styles-for-Developing-Maintainable-Code">Archived</a> from the original on 2020-10-07<span class="reference-accessdate">.    <h1 class="firstHeading" id="firstHeading" lang="en">
    Regular expression
   </h1>
   <div class="mw-body-content" id="bodyContent">
    <div class="noprint" id="siteSub">
     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
    </div>
    <div id="contentSub">
    </div>
    <div id="contentSub2">
    </div>
    <div id="jump-to-nav">
    </div>
    <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">
     Jump to navigation
    </a>
    <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">
     Jump to search
    </a>
    <div class="mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr" id="mw-content-text" lang="en">
     <div class="mw-parser-output">
      <div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">
       Sequence of characters that forms a search pattern
      </div>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       "Regex" redirects here. For the comic book, see
       <a href="/wiki/Re:Gex" title="Re:Gex">
        Re:Gex
       </a>
       .
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="504" data-file-width="875" decoding="async" height="127" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg/220px-The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg/330px-The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg/440px-The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:The_river_effect_in_justified_text.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         The match results of the pattern
         <div class="mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-ragel mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr">
          <pre><span></span><span class="o">(?</span><span class="err">&lt;</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="err">\</span><span class="o">.)</span><span class="w"> </span><span class="o">{2,}(?=</span><span class="s">[A-Z]</span><span class="o">)</span><span class="w"></span>
</pre>
         </div>
         At least two spaces are matched, but only if they occur directly after a period (.) and before an uppercase letter.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Kleene.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="800" data-file-width="562" decoding="async" height="242" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Kleene.jpg/170px-Kleene.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Kleene.jpg/255px-Kleene.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Kleene.jpg/340px-Kleene.jpg 2x" width="170"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Kleene.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Stephen_Cole_Kleene" title="Stephen Cole Kleene">
          Stephen Cole Kleene
         </a>
         , who helped invent the concept
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="1585" data-file-width="2359" decoding="async" height="148" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png/220px-Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png/330px-Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png/440px-Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Screenshot_of_MediaWiki_Blacklist.png" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/MediaWiki:Titleblacklist" title="MediaWiki:Titleblacklist">
          A blacklist
         </a>
         on
         <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia" title="Wikipedia">
          Wikipedia
         </a>
         which uses regular expressions to identify bad titles
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       A
       <b>
        regular expression
       </b>
       (shortened as
       <b>
        regex
       </b>
       or
       <b>
        regexp
       </b>
       ;
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
       also referred to as
       <b>
        rational expression
       </b>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Mitkov2003_2-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Mitkov2003-2">
         [2]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Lawson2003_3-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Lawson2003-3">
         [3]
        </a>
       </sup>
       ) is a sequence of
       <a href="/wiki/Character_(computing)" title="Character (computing)">
        characters
       </a>
       that define a
       <i>
        search
        <a href="/wiki/Pattern_matching" title="Pattern matching">
         pattern
        </a>
       </i>
       . Usually such patterns are used by
       <a href="/wiki/String-searching_algorithm" title="String-searching algorithm">
        string-searching algorithms
       </a>
       for "find" or "find and replace" operations on
       <a href="/wiki/String_(computer_science)" title="String (computer science)">
        strings
       </a>
       , or for input validation. It is a technique developed in
       <a href="/wiki/Theoretical_computer_science" title="Theoretical computer science">
        theoretical computer science
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Formal_language" title="Formal language">
        formal language
       </a>
       theory.
      </p>
      <p>
       The concept arose in the 1950s when the American mathematician
       <a href="/wiki/Stephen_Cole_Kleene" title="Stephen Cole Kleene">
        Stephen Cole Kleene
       </a>
       formalized the description of a
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Regular_language" title="Regular language">
         regular language
        </a>
       </i>
       . The concept came into common use with
       <a href="/wiki/Unix" title="Unix">
        Unix
       </a>
       text-processing utilities. Different
       <a href="/wiki/Syntax_(programming_languages)" title="Syntax (programming languages)">
        syntaxes
       </a>
       for writing regular expressions have existed since the 1980s, one being the
       <a href="/wiki/POSIX" title="POSIX">
        POSIX
       </a>
       standard and another, widely used, being the
       <a href="/wiki/Perl" title="Perl">
        Perl
       </a>
       syntax.
      </p>
      <p>
       Regular expressions are used in
       <a href="/wiki/Search_engine" title="Search engine">
        search engines
       </a>
       , search and replace dialogs of
       <a href="/wiki/Word_processor" title="Word processor">
        word processors
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Text_editor" title="Text editor">
        text editors
       </a>
       , in
       <a href="/wiki/Text_processing" title="Text processing">
        text processing
       </a>
       utilities such as
       <a href="/wiki/Sed" title="Sed">
        sed
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/AWK" title="AWK">
        AWK
       </a>
       and in
       <a href="/wiki/Lexical_analysis" title="Lexical analysis">
        lexical analysis
       </a>
       . Many
       <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">
        programming languages
       </a>
       provide regex capabilities either built-in or via
       <a href="/wiki/Library_(computing)" title="Library (computing)">
        libraries
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <div aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading" class="toc" id="toc" role="navigation">

            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
          <li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-16">
           <a href="#Possessive_matching">
            <span class="tocnumber">
             5.5
            </span>
            <span class="toctext">
             Possessive matching
            </span>
           </a>
          </li>
         </ul>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-17">
         <a href="#Patterns_for_non-regular_languages">
          <span class="tocnumber">
           6
          </span>
          <span class="toctext">
           Patterns for non-regular languages
          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-18">
         <a href="#Implementations_and_running_times">
          <span class="tocnumber">
           7
          </span>
          <span class="toctext">
           Implementations and running times
          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-19">
         <a href="#Unicode">
          <span class="tocnumber">

          </span>
          <span class="toctext">

          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-20">
         <a href="#Uses">
          <span class="tocnumber">
           9
          </span>
          <span class="toctext">
           Uses
          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-21">
         <a href="#Examples">
          <span class="tocnumber">

          </span>

          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-22">

          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-23">

          </span>
         </a>
        </li>
        <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-24">

        </li>
